==English==
[[File:2D Cartesian.svg|thumb|A point in the [[Cartesian plane]]; ''x'' is the '''abscissa'''.]]

===Etymology===
By ellipsis from {{uder|en|la|-}} [{{m|la|linea}}] {{m|la|abscissa}}, feminine of {{m|la|abscissus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|abscindō||cut off}}. See ''[[abscind]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/æbˈsɪs.ə/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-abscissa.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{hyphenation|en|ab|scis|sa}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|abscissae|abscissæ}}

# {{lb|en|geometry}} The first of the two terms by which a point is referred to, in a system of fixed [[rectilinear]] [[coordinate]] (Cartesian coordinate) axes.{{defdate|First attested in the late 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED/>
#: ''The point <math>(3,2)</math> has 3 as its '''abscissa''' and 2 as its ordinate.''
# {{lb|en|geometry}} The horizontal line representing an axis of a Cartesian coordinate system, on which the abscissa (sense above) is shown.

====Usage notes====
Originally, it referred to the portion of a line between a fixed point on that line and the intersection of that line with an [[ordinate]].<ref name=SOED>{{R:SOED5|page=8}}</ref>

